An actual leak, can be confirmed and verified with pressure sensors throughout both the ammonia & water closed coolant systems. @DJ257
Our 'escape pods' are 2 #Soyuz spacecraft on the #ISS, @AlgonquinDude  They could be used to evacuate if needed, in a worst-case scenario.
Still sorting through everything, @TK42138  Proceeding with caution. Yes, we use ammonia in the coolant loops on the outside of the #ISS.
Yes, the crew will remain in the #ISS Russian segment until it is safe to open the hatch and ingress the USOS. @MightyFine89 @theoddsociety
Analyzing the situation, with crew safety our #1 priority. @SpaceKate Exercising due diligence to keep the crew from exposure to a hazard.
Yes, alarms on the #ISS were triggered just after 9:00am GMT when a pressure increase was detected in a Node-2 water loop. @theoddsociety
The severity of the failure will dictate the complexity of recovery, @Estebs1978 A bad sensor or errant reading will be our best case today.
There are 2 #Soyuz spacecraft attached to the #ISS, @CnLila They are our ride from & to Earth...and our 'lifeboat' in case of an evacuation.
We have more work ahead, @lionellosacchi @SpaceKate The #ISS crew trains & prepares for just such a moment, and they reacted with precision.
Each #ISS module has a metal hatch at all passageways, @Danilon62 At the interface of the Russian/US segments, we close & latch the hatch.
Yes, 'dp/dt' or 'delta-pressure/delta-time' is a measure of decreasing / increasing pressure. @DJ257 Monitored in fluids & cabin atmosphere.

Thank you, Graham! @GrahamBowes The crew is safe & secure in the Russian Segment; plenty of food, water, breathing air, and of course a loo.
Water is our coolant medium inside...it flows through heat exchangers to transfer heat to ammonia, our coolant medium outside the #ISS.
Sensors initially detected a small positive dp/dt into the cabin and accumulator quantity increase in the Node-2 low temperature water loop.
ISS crew is safe in the Russian Segment. Our team in Mission Control is confirming what is believed to be a false ammonia leak indication.
